      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The critique that substantive due process is merely judicial activism is a common, yet deeply flawed, complaint from those who fear judicial power. While some rulings are certainly controversial, the doctrine is fundamentally rooted in the Lockean concept of natural rights that predate government. To dismiss it as mere personal opinion is to ignore the historical struggle to embed inherent human dignity into the law.",
      "source": "target",
